=Agriculture

Pottery (30 000 BC)

#Neolithic Revolution
hunter-gatherer to agriculture

#Domestication
dogs (13 000 BC)
Middle East
- wheat, barley, pea, lentil, chickpea, flax, pig, sheep, goat (10 000 BC)
America
- maize, bean, squash, potato, tomato, peanut, llama (7000 BC)
- sunflower, cocoa, cotton, pineapple (4000 BC)
East Asia
- rice, soybean, millet, chicken (7000 BC)
- tea, peach, silkworm (4000 BC)
Southeast Asia
- sugarcane, bananas (7000 BC)
- coconut (4000 BC)
horses (3000 BC)

Irrigation (6000 BC): Egypt, Middle East

Crop rotation
- Three-field system: cereal / legumes / fallow (11 century)

Green Revolution: fertilizers (1970s)


=Maths and Astronomy
Anaxagoras (~500 BC): Moon reflects light of Sun, Sun is star
Archimedes (~250 BC): Pi value
Eratosthenes (~250 BC): Earth circumference, prime numbers algorithm
Hipparchus (~150 BC): size and distances of Moon and Sun
--
Zu Chongzhi (~500): Pi value
Aryabhata (~500): solar and lunar eclipse, Pi value
Brahmagupta (~650) zero and negative numbers
--
Leonhard Euler
Carl Friedrich Gauss
Georg Cantor

=Transport

Wheel (3500 BC)

=Ships
Galley: oars for propulsion
- Penteconter: 25 oars per side
- Bireme: two banks of oars
- Trireme: three banks of oars
- Quinquereme (~350 BC): three banks, 2-2-1 men per oar
Junk: flat bottom, one or more decks, sails divided into panels for propulsion
Cog (10th century): single mast and square sail for propulsion
Carrack (14th century): multiple masts, single deck, sails for propulsion
Galleon (16th century): multiple masts and decks, sails for propulsion
Clipper (18th century): fast, narrow, many sails

Karl Drais: Velocipede (1818)
Carl Benz: Car (1886)
Ferdinand von Zeppelin: Airship (1900)
Wright brothers: Airplane (1904)
Henry Ford: Car mass production (1908)
Hindenburg disaster: end of airships (1937)
Igor Sikorsky: Helicopter (1939)

